{A jump to 2NT would be descriptive, but your first goal is to seek a Major suit fit. When you have two 4-card Majors you should respond "up-the-line" so you bid 1\H. Partner says 2\H.  

Partner would not support your \H suit without 4 cards so you have an 8-card Major fit. There is no point in bidding \Ss.

Partner has at least 13 points and you have 13 so you bid the game.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \D10.

<b>East plays 4\H. South leads the \D10.</b>

To 

Losers: \S 0 : \H 1 : \D 0 : \C 3 : Total = 4

There is nothing you can do about losing the Ace of trumps. The three \C losers would only happen if South has the \CA and North wins a trick early, (say with the \HA), and leads a \C through your \CK.

You can take care of this possibility by discarding a \C from dummy <b>BEFORE</b> you play trumps. So win the \DK, and play \SA, \SK, \SQ, discarding dummy's \C3 on the last one. Then pull trumps. You will end up losing two \Cs and the \HA.

Visualize what would have happened if you had taken the first trick and immediately tried to pull trumps.

North would win his \HA and would switch to a black suit to lead up to dummy's weakness. In this case he would surely lead the \CQ, and you would lose three \C tricks and be down before you started.

Making a PLAN is a necessary part of being a good Declarer and Visualizing what might happen is a necessary part of making a Plan.}
