{It is tempting to bid 3NT and hope partner can use your \C suit. But you have something very important in your hand - a 4-card \H suit.

So you bid 2\C. (Stayman, not your \C suit!) Partner replies 2\H. What do you say next? 

He who knows, goes. You have 11 points and 4 \Hs. Partner has at least 15 points and 4 \Hs. So you bid the game. 

East would play 4\H.

Click 

West plays 4\H. North leads the \SQ.

<b>West plays 4\H. North leads the \SQ.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 1 or 2 : \D 1 : \C 0 : Total = 2 or 3

This PLAN looks awfully simple. Win the \S, play \HA, \HK, then give up a \H. When you get back in run the \Cs.

But when you play the second high \H South shows out.

Make another Plan, then  

<b>West plays 4\H. North leads the \SQ.</b>

Let's start over. Play \HK, then \HA. South shows out. If you play another \H North will pull all the trumps and they will start winning \D tricks. Lots of \D tricks.

So don't lead the third \H. Leave North with his two master trumps and start playing \C winners. North will eventually ruff in with one of his high trumps and perhaps take a \D trick. But you have trump control and can get in again and reach dummy with a ruff to continue \Cs. All North can do is get his one more trump.

When you have pulled a couple of rounds of trumps and the defenders hold a master trump it is usually good technique to leave it out. No sense using two of yours to get one of theirs.

This hand is much rarer - leaving TWO master trumps out. But you can see that it is the correct technique.}
[Play "W"]SQ

