{You have 15 points and you have a balanced distribution. You should open 1NT. It is true that you do not have \Cs stopped, but you are not required to have a stopper in all the suits to open 1NT. Partner jumps to 3NT and you pass.

West plays 3NT. North leads the \HQ.

<b>West plays 3NT. North leads the \HQ.</b>

Winner count: \S 1 : \H 2 : \D 1 : \C 2 : Total = 6

In many Notrump hands it is good to hold up to disrupt the defender's communications. In this hand you have a double-stopper in \Hs but only a single stop in \Ss and \Ds so win the first trick.

You need 3 more tricks from the \C suit. As long as the \Cs split 3-2, which is very likely, you can set up the tricks you need. <b>BUT</b>, if you just play \CA \CK and then a small one you'll be sorry. Those extra three \Cs will be established as winners but you will have no entry to them.

Instead, you play your \C4 to the second trick and also play a low card from dummy. This is called Ducking the trick. South/North will certainly win that trick, but you are in control. You can win whatever suit they play and you still have that \C7 to reach dummy's solid \Cs.

You can see that with \Cs splitting 3-2 the Duck insures the contract.

But just imagine you had played \CA, \CK, \C2. At that point \C 9 6 5 would all be winners, but don't think South is going to let you reach dummy with either of those two Jacks!}
[Play "W"]HQ

