{A jump to 2NT would not be a terrible bid. But it is more important to show your 4-card Major.

So you bid 1\S instead. Partner raises to 2\S.

It's another case of <b>HE WHO KNOWS, GOES</b>. You know you have at least 26 points and 8 \Ss. Of course you trust that partner would not raise a suit you bid as responder with only 3 trumps. So you bid 4\S.

North plays 4\S. East leads the \HK. The defense takes the first three \H tricks, then switch to a \C.

<b>North plays 4\S. East leads the \HK. The defense takes the first three \H tricks, then switch to a \C.</b>

Losers: \S ? : \H 3 : \D 0 : \C 0 : Total = 3?

It kinda makes you wish you'd bid 2NT after all doesn't it?

At least the picture is clear. Very clear. You have no wiggle room left so you must bring in the \Ss without losing a trick. So East <b>MUST</b> have the \SK. Therefore you assume East does hold the \SK. 

Suppose you lead the \SQ. East will play his \SK and force you to play dummy's \SA. Then one of the defenders will win the third \S with the \ST or \S9.

No, you only have one chance to make this contract - East must hold a doubleton \S K x. So you lead a <b>SMALL</b> \S from your hand and finesse dummy's \SJ. Then play the \SA, dropping East's \SK, then pull the last trump with the \SQ.

The reason you must not lead the \SQ is that East will always cover and that  will force you to use two of your honors on one trick.

Since you would only have one more honor you'd be bound to lose a trick.}
[Play "W"]HK

