{You estimate your hand has 6 playing tricks. That is reasonable for a preemptive 3\H bid. East overcalls 3\S and partner bids 4\H. Everybody passes.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \SK.

<b>North plays 4\H. East leads the \SK.</b>

Losers: \S 1 : \H 1 : \D 0 : \C 1 : Total = 3

This looks way too easy. If the \H finesse works and the \C finesse works you could make 6. It is when things look too easy that you should look for danger! What if you play the \SA and West ruffs. What if West also gets a trick with the \HK and East gets a trick with the \CQ. What with your \S loser you would be down 1.

East probably has a 7-card suit to overcall at the 3-level, so if you play the \SA West will ruff and one of your winners will disappear. So don't play the \SA. Duck and let East win the trick while West shows out as expected. East will lead the \SQ and you duck again. So East will lead the \SJ and you duck one more time, but now you can ruff in your hand.

Lead your \HQ and finesse, West winning the \HK. West will probably return a \D which you win in dummy. Play the \HA. Then ruff a \D to get back to your hand and pull any trumps left out. Play a \C to dummy's \CA and at long last play dummy's \SA and discard your \C loser.

You always had 10 winners in this hand, as long as one of them didn't disappear.

To make sure the \SA didn't disappear you had to hold it until West no longer had a trump. }
