{You certainly have a Notrump type hand, but you are too strong to open 2NT.

With 23 points you open 2\C. Partner says 2\D.

What is your next bid? 

Now you show your 23 point, balanced hand by bidding 2NT. This is not forcing on partner, he might pass.

However, he doesn't pass, he says 3\C.

What is your next bid? 

This is no different than a 3\C bid after an opening 2NT. It is Stayman.

So you bid your 4-card \H suit and partner bids the game.

North plays 4\H. East leads the \C2. The defense takes three \C tricks, then plays a small \D.

<b>North plays 4\H. East leads the \C2. The defense takes three \C tricks, then plays a small \D.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 1 : \D 0 : \C 3 : Total = 4

Since you've already lost the 3 \C tricks the Goal of your Plan is simple - <b>Don't Lose the</b> \H.

That makes the card assumptions simple also - <b>West Must Have the \HK.</b>

You only have one dummy entry so once you use it you must remain in dummy until you have finished finessing. If West has the \H K x you can't go wrong. If he has \H K x x you will have to play with care. And if he has \H K x x x you must play perfectly.

Enter dummy with the \SK. Lead the \H9 and let it ride. Assuming it wins, lead the \HJ and play your \H10 under it. Now lead a small \H and finesse the \HQ. This way you get all four \H tricks. No other way will work.

To prove that only the original \H9 play will work . . <b>VISUALIZE</b>:

(1) That your first play from dummy was  \HJ, and you played \H3 from your hand. The next \H would have to be taken in your hand and you no longer have a finesse.

(2) That your first play from dummy was the \HJ and you played \H10 under it. To stay in dummy one more trick you would have to play the \H9 and put the \H3 under it. But when you play the \H9 West will cover with his \HK. You can win with the \HA but are left with \H Q 3 and the lead will be in your hand. You will lose a trick to West's \H 8 5.}
