{You open 1\H, South overcalls 1\S and partner passes.

You shouldn't let South steal from you so you will bid your \Hs again. You must decide between 2\H and 3\H. Given that partner might have had a pretty decent hand yet still have to pass, you decide to go with 3\H. Partner bids 4\H. 

East plays 4\H. South leads the \SQ.

<b>East plays 4\H. South leads the \SQ.</b>

Losers: \S 2 : \H 1 : \D 2 : \C 0 : Total = 5

Win the \SK, then enter dummy with the \CA and play another \S toward your \SA. You do this to prevent North ruffing your high \S. Next you lead the \S2 and ruff with dummy's \HK. Ruff a \C to get back to your hand and ruff the \S7 with dummy's \H9. North may over-ruff this, but only with a trump trick he was going to win anyway.

You will lose two \Ds and the \HQ but no more.

It is tempting to ruff the first \S with dummy's \H9, hoping to sneak that through then ruff the second one with \HK. 

The problem is that North would have over-ruffed the \H9 and then played another \H and you would not have gotten to ruff either \S,}
